arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The project files are arranged in series according to country. Each state within the United States and every country or geographical area was assigned a three-digit number by RF staff. In addition, letters signifying program areas are used: for example, "A" indicates a grant in the Medical Sciences, and "C" Nursing. Material is organized within these letter/program subdivisions alphabetically by grant title. A grant title usually consists of a heading that includes the name of the institution or individual that received the grant. Thus each grant, or project, is filed individually in one or more folders.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Types of records include: project files.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Records more than 10 years old are open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Confidential material in this record group has been segregated and is inaccessible. Each pertinent file is open to research, and physical removal of the segregated material within each file is not necessary. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact a RAC archivist.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Rockefeller Foundation has title, copyright, and literary rights in the collection, in so far as it holds them. Rockefeller Archive Center has authority to grant permission to cite and publish archival material from the collection.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This material, mostly from 1913 to 1942, relates to funded projects originated by international organizations or involving more than one country. Included in this designation are organizations directly connected with the Rockefeller Foundation, such as the International Health Division (which was a part of the Foundation that was governed separately until 1951); organizations indirectly related to the Foundation, such as the Spelman Fund of New York and the China Medical Board, Inc.; and other, independent organizations that received support from the Foundation. Much of the material concerns the work of the International Health Division. There is a large section on the war relief of the Foundation (1914 to 1918). Additional items of interest are a progress report on nursing education (1928), an anthropological survey (1932 to 1933), and the files on international studies and international relations.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The 100 series is divided into 18 subseries as follow:
100 (No program letter, general material which does not fit into a particular program area)
100 A Medical sciences (research conducted in medical schools or medical schools or medical research institutes, research directly applicable to the mental and physical health of human beings)
100 C Nursing (nursing education, public health nursing)
100 EL Public health fellowships, scholarships, training awards
100 F Declinations (only declinations of exceptional interest are retained)
100 L Public health education (schools of hygiene and public health)

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Material, mostly 1913-1942, relating to projects originated by international organizations or involving more than one country. Included in this designation are organizations directly connected with the Rockefeller Foundation, such as the International Health Division (which was a part of the Foundation governed separately until 1951); organizations indirectly related to the Foundation, such as the Spelman Fund of New York and the China Medical Board, Inc.; and other, independent organizations which received support from the Foundation. Much of the material concerns the work of the International Health Division. There is a large section on the war relief of the Foundation (1914-1918). Additional items of interest are a progress report on nursing education (1928), an anthropological survey (1932-1933), and the files on international studies and international relations.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series includes material for grants given to organizations that are national in scope but that fall outside the Foundation's established program divisions. Files are organized alphabetically. This series includes documentation of grants given as the result of the founder's designation and grants to such institutions as the American Baptist Home Mission Society, the American Council on Education, Biological Abstracts, a bird refuge in Louisiana, the Bureau of Municipal Research, the National Committee for Mental Hygiene, the National Research Council, and prominent universities such as Johns Hopkins, Harvard and Yale. Also included in this series are files on the Foundation's support of the Emergency Committee in Aid of Displaced Foreign Scholars and its support for Refugee Scholars during the 1930s and 1940s.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The 200 Series is divided into 15 subseries according to program. Because this is a large series, each subseries is described separately.

odd.head: General note

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Most of the files in this section date from the 1930s and 1940s. The Foundation's program in the medical sciences during this period was directed by Dr. Alan Gregg and was concentrated in psychiatry and neurology and related subjects: neuroanatomy, heredity, endocrinology, neuropathology, child guidance, industrial psychology, and sex research. Emphasis was placed on worker training, selected research projects, and measures to improve or extend the application of existing knowledge. The medical sciences program also devoted part of its resources to the development of university teaching departments of public health. The program was conceived to be complementary to the natural sciences program in human biology. Although it developed out of the old Division of Medical Education of the Foundation, the Medical Sciences division had no program in medical education in the United States, except for a small program of post-war medical fellowship grants to leading universities.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: In this small subseries, most of the material originated between the years 1918 and 1935. The files contain information relating to the development of public health nursing and to education for nurses in the eastern United States. Uniformity of standards in nursing training was the Foundation's main concern. At first the Foundation's program in nursing was administered by Edwin Embree as part of the program of the Division of Studies. After the reorganization of 1927-1938, nursing was transferred, first to the province of Richard M. Pearce and the Division of Medical Education and later to the International Health Division.

Personnel in nursing in the Rockefeller Foundation included F. Elizabeth Crowell, who worked mostly in the field, and Mary Beard, former president of the National Organization for Public Health Nursing, who worked in the United States from 1925 to 1938. There is much of her correspondence in these files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The Foundation's program in natural sciences developed from the old programs of the IEB and GEB. Under the direction of Wickliffe Rose, those organizations emphasized mathematics, physics, and chemistry. After a trial period of 1929 to 1932, during which the natural sciences division had five directors or acting directors, Warren Weaver was appointed director, remaining until 1951. A new program was developed, at first called "vital processes" and later "modern experimental biology," to meet the desire of the Trustees for a people-oriented program based on the idea that the natural sciences were essential to medicine. The programs in medical science and natural science were intended to be complementary.

This group of files contains material mostly from the 1930s and 1940s relating to research projects in subjects such as biophysics, biochemistry, genetics, and physiology. A number of European refugee scholars were aided under this program. The application of physical and chemical techniques to biology, genetics, and nutrition was of special interest. There are no files relating to agriculture in this subseries.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The Foundation's earliest program in the humanities was inherited from the International Education Board and the General Education Board. Edward Capps, director in 1929 and 1930, administered a program concentrating on teaching and research in classical studies, emphasizing fluid research funds. For two years humanities was without a director until David H. Stevens was appointed in 1932. Subsequently a new program was developed emphasizing improved world communication through national libraries and teaching of essential languages. In early years of 1932 to 1939, this program was concentrated on four main geographical areas: the Far East, Latin America, the Slavic region, and the United States. Support was also given to early experiments in microfilm and radio research.

During the war years, 1939 to 1945, early experience in mass communication proved valuable, and support was given for work in microfilm, especially for preservation of endangered records; for radio listening centers and propaganda analysis; and for public opinion polling. Language training continued to be important. European humanists were aided in their efforts to reach this country and resume productive lives.

After 1945, although support for Far East and Slavic studies continued, there was a new emphasis on America in the Foundation's program, seen in grants for regional studies and grants in aid of American scholarly publishing.
Humanities in creative aspects had support chiefly in the advance of community and university drama. A substantial grant was made to start the Berkshire Music Center.
David H. Stevens remained director of the humanities program until 1950. There was no national foundation for the arts at this time.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The Rockefeller Foundation took over from the Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial a well-developed program in the social sciences. This program had emphasized the promotion of fundamental and applied social sciences and research in the areas of social disturbance and problems of socially maladjusted groups.

In 1933, the Trustees of the Foundation called for a program in human relations complementary to the medical science program in psychiatry and the natural sciences program in human biology. A program was developed that included international relations, economic stabilization, social security, the public administration. Special objectives of this program were the training of technical and administrative personnel and creating a liaison between practitioner and research groups in these fields. Grants were made to organizations such as the Foreign Policy Association, the National Bureau of Economic Research, the Institute of Pacific Relations, and the Brookings Institution. Projects at leading universities were supported.

Other fields in which the Foundation had an interest include housing, cultural anthropology, and criminology. These were never fully developed. There was a strong interest in strengthening the social science field, especially through such organizations as the American Association of Schools of Social Work and the Social Science Research Council.
Directors of the social science program were Edmund E. Day (1929-1937); Sydnor H. Walker, Acting (1937-1938); and Joseph H. Willits (1939-1954).
